@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

 @{b}What is AXOLR II?@{ub}
 =================

   AXOLR II is 'onliner' program for every BBS-software which supports
   stdio-types of programs (it means that BBS program can start DOS-
   programs from BBS). The whole world is full of different kinds of
   good onliners, so why did I program this? Because world has no
   onliner that would work well with my BBS-software which, at the moment,
   can load only stdio-types of programs. This version of AXOLR should
   wor in every good BBS-software. If it doesn't work in yours, you
   should immediately change software :)

   At first AXOLR-program was designed only for AXsh BBS-software but because
   its stdio, I programmed it also for others. Earlier verisons used AXsh's 
   who()-function to find out users name so that's why it didn't work in
   other programs. Now AXOLR takes users name as an argument.

@endnode
@node "Requires" "System Requirements"

   @{b}Requirements@{ub}
   ============

     - Amiga 500 - 4000 or better. In the near future AXOLR should work in
       other computers too. UNIX and MSDOS versions are coming soon.
     - at least Amiga OS 1.2 (not tested) or better.
     - BBS-program or program which serves the same purpose. Works also from
       DOS, so BBS-program isn't must but recommended

      
    This program has been tested with these computers:

     * Amiga1200, os3.1, 2Mb Chip Mem, 2Mb Fast Mem, 68EC020 @ 15 | AXsh v1.33-beta
     * Amiga500, os2.04, 512K Chip Mem, 512k Fast Mem, 68000 @  7 | AXsh v1.32

@endnode
@node "Setup" "Installation"

   @{b}Setup@{ub}
   =====

     AXOLR II's setup should be easy, but its easiness depends much from 
     which BBS-software you use. If you don't know how to setup Stdio(DOS)
     programs in you BBS, then you must look instructions from your
     BBS-software's manual.

     1. @{b}Copy@{ub} AXOLR2 into directory where you keep your 'doors'.

     2. @{b}Start@{ub} AXOLR2 and you should get to AXOLR2's inner configuration 
        program, where you can set data file location and number of lines
        in AXOLR2. Number of lines is recommended to be about 15 and
        data files name and location you can decide self. My data file name 
        and location is axhs:etc/axolr2.dat

     3. @{b}Setup@{ub} the program in your BBS.

     You can see AXOLR II's arguments (options) with AXOLR2 -h command.
     Anyway, here is list of them:
     
AXOLR II Oct  8 1996 17:26:07 v2.0[AMIGA] by Tommi "Shaman" Leino / Diverse
Usage: axolr2 [-ac7ivh?] [-r <rows>] <username>

 -a         accept anonymous messages
 -c         configure axolr2
 -7         use sf7 -> iso-8859-1 character set conversion (sf)
 -i         use ibm -> iso-8859-1 character set conversion (sf)
 -v         displays brief version information
 -h, -?     displays this helptext
 -r <rows>  set user's rows, default: 23
<username>  set user's username, max 10 characters

      @{b}How to setup AXOLR to AXsh-software:@{ub}
      ------------------------------------ 
      
       1. @{b}copy@{ub} AXOLR2 axsh:bin/-directory.
       2. @{b}edit@{ub} axsh:etc/globallogin file and add this row there:

           @{b}axolr2 $user@{ub}

          You can see AXOLR2's options with AXOLR2 -h command. I recommend
          setting up at least -i and -r options. In that case you would
          add this row in axsh:etc/globallogin directory: 
          
           @{b}axolr2 -i -r $rows $user@{ub}

       3. edit axsh:etc/rc file and add this row after second $visitor:-text:

           @{b}f axsh:bin/axolr2@{ub}
      
  That's it!

@endnode
